article.description:
Janell Burse scored a season-high 27 points, and Lauren Jackson had 10 of her 21 down the stretch to lead the
surging Seattle Storm to a 79-68 victory Friday night over the
Charlotte Sting.
article.headline: Burse leads Seattle with 27, Jackson adds 21 in win
article.linkText: Storm dispatch Sting for fifth win in a row
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Seattle Storm coach Anne Donovan said her team
needs more performances like the one Janell Burse delivered Friday
night in a 79-68 victory over the Charlotte Sting.

"JB, obviously had a monster game," Donovan said. "They kept
bringing posts at her and she just had her way. We can use more of
that from her."

Burse made 11 of 13 from the field and had six rebounds in
scoring her season-high 27 points. Lauren Jackson had 10 of her 21
down the stretch to lead the Storm.

"My teammates gave me some really good passes and found me when
I was open and Lauren was double-teamed. I credit them for finding
me," Burse said.

"Burse was the X factor," Sting coach Trudy Lacey said. "Once
she got on a roll, it was tough to stop her."

Burse scored the game-winning basket in their previous meeting
on June 12 when the Storm prevailed 62-60 in Charlotte.

Sue Bird had 17 points and seven assists as the Storm (13-10)
extended their season-best winning streak to five games. The Sting
are 0-11 on the road and a league worst 3-20 overall.

The Storm said they were fortunate their opponent was the Sting
and not the Los Angeles Sparks whom they host on Sunday at Key
Arena.

"We got the bad game out of our system," Bird said. "Every
championship team I've been on, you win games on an off-night.
Hopefully, tonight we got that game out of our system."

Jia Perkins led the Sting with 21 points. Sheri Sam and Tangela
Smith added 12 points each. Perkins started in place of Allison
Feaster who was injured during a loss to Sacramento.

Jackson scored 10 of the Storm's 12 points in a six-minute span
in the second half as Seattle stretched a 60-52 lead to 72-59.

"It was a slog out there," Jackson said. "It was a game that
we could never put them away."

Burse scored 11 points and Bird nine as the Storm led 33-23 at
halftime.

Sam, was a member of the Storm championship team last year, was
given her championship ring before the game and received a standing
ovation. She and Perkins had eight points apiece for the Sting in
the opening half.

"Getting that ring brings a closure on last year's
championship. It was good to come back," Sam said.

Sam engaged in lots of on-court chatter with her former
teammates but it did not distract the Storm.
